Below is a **single, self‑contained C‑wrapper** that can be compiled directly into a Lua module (e.g. `blocksci.so`).  
It shows a clean, “pandas‑style” Lua API, a fast hot‑path implementation, and all the necessary C‑stubs that talk to the BlockSci C++ iterator.

---

## 1.  The Lua‑facing API (what the user will see)

```lua
local blocksci = require "blocksci"

-- Open a BlockSci database (the path you passed to the C++ library)
local db = blocksci.open("/path/to/blocksci/db")

-- -------------------------------------------------
-- 1) Walk every block and run user code (the hot path)
-- -------------------------------------------------
db:for_each(function (blk)          -- blk is a lightweight userdata
    -- blk:height()      -> uint64
    -- blk:hash()        -> hex string
    -- blk:time()        -> unix timestamp (seconds)
    -- blk:tx_count()    -> number of transactions in the block
    --
    -- Example: count blocks after a certain date
    if blk:time() > 1609459200 then   -- 2021‑01‑01 00:00:00 UTC
        print(string.format("Block %d (%s) – %d txs",
                blk:height(), blk:hash(), blk:tx_count()))
    end
    -- returning `false` aborts the iteration early
    return true
end)

-- -------------------------------------------------
-- 2) Pull a single block out of the database (optional)
-- -------------------------------------------------
local b = db:block_at_height(123456)   -- returns the same userdata type as above
print(b:hash())
```

### Design goals that make this fast

| Goal | How it is achieved |
|------|--------------------|
| **Zero allocation per iteration** | A **single** `Block` userdata is created when the iterator is built. Its internal C++ `Block` struct is overwritten on every step; the Lua object stays the same. |
| **Direct field access** | The block fields are exposed as **C‑functions** (`blk:height()`, `blk:hash()`, …) that read the already‑filled C++ structure. No tables are built per block. |
| **One Lua call per block** | The hot loop lives entirely in C; the only Lua interaction is a single `lua_pcall` of the user‑supplied callback. |
| **Early‑exit support** | The callback may return `false` (or any falsy value) to stop the iteration without extra checks. |
| **Safety** | The iterator holds a reference to the user callback (`luaL_ref`) so the function cannot be GC‑collected while the loop runs. Errors in the user callback are propagated as Lua errors. |

---

## 2.  The C / C++ binding (everything you need to compile)

> **Copy‑paste the whole file** into `blocksci_lua.c`.  
> It compiles both as C and C++ (the only C++ part is the mock BlockSci API).  
> Replace the mock BlockSci definitions with the real ones from your library.

```c
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 * blocksci_lua.c
 *   Lua binding for BlockSci – a high‑performance per‑block iterator.
 *
 * Build (Linux/macOS):
 *   gcc -shared -fPIC -I/usr/include/lua5.4 -std=c++17 \
 *       -o blocksci.so blocksci_lua.c -llua5.4 -lstdc++
 *
 *   (adjust include / lib paths for your Lua version)
 *
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#include <lua.h>
#include <lauxlib.h>
#include <lualib.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <stdint.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdio.h>

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   Mock BlockSci API ----------------------------------------------------
 *   Replace this section with the real BlockSci headers.
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

/* Simple stand‑in for a real BlockSci Block structure */
typedef struct {
    uint64_t height;      /* block height (0‑based)               */
    const char *hash;     /* hex string, owned by the DB object   */
    uint32_t tx_count;    /* number of transactions in the block  */
    uint64_t timestamp;   /* UNIX epoch seconds                   */
} BS_Block;

/* Very small iterator – in reality BlockSci will give you something
 * similar but more featureful. */
typedef struct {
    const char *db_path;   /* just for illustration                */
    uint64_t   cur;        /* current height                        */
    uint64_t   max;        /* pretend 800 000 000 blocks             */
} BS_BlockIterator;

/* Open a DB – returns a pointer that must be freed with BS_close_db() */
static BS_BlockIterator *BS_open(const char *db_path)
{
    BS_BlockIterator *it = (BS_BlockIterator *)malloc(sizeof(*it));
    it->db_path = db_path;
    it->cur = 0;
    it->max = 800000000ULL;            /* pretend huge dataset */
    return it;
}

/* Close a DB – frees the iterator */
static void BS_close(BS_BlockIterator *it)
{
    free(it);
}

/* Fill *out with the next block; return true on success, false when done */
static bool BS_next(BS_BlockIterator *it, BS_Block *out)
{
    if (it->cur >= it->max) return false;
    out->height    = it->cur;
    out->tx_count  = (uint32_t)( (it->cur % 1000) + 1 );
    out->timestamp = 1231006505ULL + it->cur * 600;               /* genesis + 10‑min */
    /* Fake hash – not a real SHA‑256, just a printable placeholder */
    static char hashbuf[65];
    snprintf(hashbuf, sizeof(hashbuf), "%064llx", (unsigned long long)it->cur);
    out->hash = hashbuf;
    ++it->cur;
    return true;
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   End of mock BlockSci API – replace with the real one.
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#ifdef __cplusplus
}
#endif
/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */


/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   Lua userdata definitions
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* Forward declarations for metatables */
static const char *BLOCK_ITER_MT   = "BlockSci.BlockIter";
static const char *BLOCK_MT        = "BlockSci.Block";

/* The iterator userdata – holds a pointer to the real C++ iterator */
typedef struct {
    BS_BlockIterator *it;          /* owned, freed on GC */
    int               cb_ref;      /* reference to the Lua callback */
} lua_BlockIter;

/* The block userdata – a thin wrapper around the C++ BS_Block struct.
 * The same userdata object is reused for every iteration step.       */
typedef struct {
    BS_Block block;                /* fields are overwritten each step */
    bool     valid;                /* true after the first successful next() */
} lua_Block;

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   Helper macros
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#define CHECK_ARG(L, cond, idx, msg) \
    if (!(cond)) return luaL_error((L), "argument %d: %s", (idx), (msg))

#define luaL_checkuserdata(L, idx, name) \
    (luaL_checkudata((L), (idx), (name)))

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   Block methods (exposed to Lua)
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static int lua_Block_height(lua_State *L)
{
    lua_Block *b = (lua_Block *)luaL_checkuserdata(L, 1, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_pushinteger(L, (lua_Integer)b->block.height);
    return 1;
}
static int lua_Block_hash(lua_State *L)
{
    lua_Block *b = (lua_Block *)luaL_checkuserdata(L, 1, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_pushstring(L, b->block.hash);
    return 1;
}
static int lua_Block_tx_count(lua_State *L)
{
    lua_Block *b = (lua_Block *)luaL_checkuserdata(L, 1, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_pushinteger(L, (lua_Integer)b->block.tx_count);
    return 1;
}
static int lua_Block_time(lua_State *L)
{
    lua_Block *b = (lua_Block *)luaL_checkuserdata(L, 1, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_pushinteger(L, (lua_Integer)b->block.timestamp);
    return 1;
}

/* __gc for block – nothing to free (the struct lives inside the iterator) */
static int lua_Block_gc(lua_State *L)
{
    /* No action needed – the block memory is owned by the iterator */
    (void)L;
    return 0;
}

/* Register block methods */
static const luaL_Reg block_methods[] = {
    {"height",   lua_Block_height},
    {"hash",     lua_Block_hash},
    {"tx_count", lua_Block_tx_count},
    {"time",     lua_Block_time},
    {NULL, NULL}
};

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   Iterator methods
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* Internal helper: push the *single* block userdata that lives inside the iterator */
static lua_Block *push_iterator_block(lua_State *L, lua_BlockIter *it)
{
    /* The block userdata is stored as an upvalue of the iterator’s
     * metatable – we allocate it lazily the first time it is needed.   */
    lua_getuservalue(L, 1);               /* 1 = iterator userdata */
    if (lua_isnil(L, -1)) {                /* no block yet */
        lua_pop(L,1);
        lua_Block *b = (lua_Block *)lua_newuserdata(L, sizeof(lua_Block));
        b->valid = false;
        /* set its metatable */
        luaL_getmetatable(L, BLOCK_MT);
        lua_setmetatable(L, -2);
        /* store as the iterator’s uservalue */
        lua_pushvalue(L, -1);              /* copy */
        lua_setuservalue(L, 1);            /* iterator[1] = block */
        return b;
    } else {
        lua_Block *b = (lua_Block *)lua_touserdata(L, -1);
        lua_pop(L,1);
        return b;
    }
}

/* iterator:for_each(callback) */
static int lua_BlockIter_for_each(lua_State *L)
{
    lua_BlockIter *it = (lua_BlockIter *)luaL_checkuserdata(L, 1, BLOCK_ITER_MT);
    luaL_checktype(L, 2, LUA_TFUNCTION);           /* the user callback */
    /* Store a reference to the callback (so it survives the loop) */
    lua_pushvalue(L, 2);
    it->cb_ref = luaL_ref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX);   /* cb_ref is now an int */

    /* Grab (or create) the reusable block userdata */
    lua_Block *blk = push_iterator_block(L, it);
    (void)blk; /* silence unused warning – we’ll reuse it each iteration */

    /* Main hot loop – completely in C, only a single lua_pcall per block */
    BS_Block cur;
    while (BS_next(it->it, &cur)) {
        /* Fill the block userdata */
        blk->block = cur;
        blk->valid = true;

        /* Call the Lua callback:  callback(block) */
        lua_rawgeti(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, it->cb_ref);   /* push function */
        lua_pushvalue(L, -2);                            /* push block userdata */
        if (lua_pcall(L, 1, 1, 0) != LUA_OK) {
            /* Propagate the error – clean up the callback reference */
            const char *msg = lua_tostring(L, -1);
            luaL_error(L, "callback error: %s", msg);
        }
        /* The callback may return false/nil to abort early */
        int keep = lua_toboolean(L, -1);
        lua_pop(L, 1);                                   /* discard return */
        if (!keep) break;
    }

    /* Release the reference to the Lua function */
    luaL_unref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, it->cb_ref);
    it->cb_ref = LUA_NOREF;

    return 0;   /* no return values */
}

/* iterator:block_at_height(h)  – random access (optional helper) */
static int lua_BlockIter_block_at_height(lua_State *L)
{
    lua_BlockIter *it = (lua_BlockIter *)luaL_checkuserdata(L, 1, BLOCK_ITER_MT);
    uint64_t height = (uint64_t)luaL_checkinteger(L, 2);

    /* In a real implementation you would seek into the DB.  Here we just
     * simulate by resetting the iterator and walking forward – O(N) – but
     * the API stays the same. */
    BS_close(it->it);
    it->it = BS_open(it->it->db_path);
    BS_Block cur;
    bool ok = false;
    while (BS_next(it->it, &cur)) {
        if (cur.height == height) { ok = true; break; }
    }
    if (!ok) return luaL_error(L, "block %llu not found", (unsigned long long)height);

    lua_Block *blk = push_iterator_block(L, it);
    blk->block = cur;
    blk->valid = true;
    return 1;   /* return the block userdata */
}

/* __gc for iterator – free the C++ iterator and release the callback ref */
static int lua_BlockIter_gc(lua_State *L)
{
    lua_BlockIter *it = (lua_BlockIter *)luaL_checkuserdata(L, 1, BLOCK_ITER_MT);
    if (it->it) BS_close(it->it);
    if (it->cb_ref != LUA_NOREF)
        luaL_unref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, it->cb_ref);
    return 0;
}

/* Register iterator methods */
static const luaL_Reg iterator_methods[] = {
    {"for_each",        lua_BlockIter_for_each},
    {"block_at_height", lua_BlockIter_block_at_height},
    {NULL, NULL}
};

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   Library entry point – blocksci.open(path) → iterator userdata
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static int lua_blocksci_open(lua_State *L)
{
    const char *path = luaL_checkstring(L, 1);
    BS_BlockIterator *it = BS_open(path);
    if (!it) return luaL_error(L, "cannot open BlockSci DB at %s", path);

    lua_BlockIter *ud = (lua_BlockIter *)lua_newuserdata(L, sizeof(lua_BlockIter));
    ud->it     = it;
    ud->cb_ref = LUA_NOREF;

    /* Set iterator metatable */
    luaL_getmetatable(L, BLOCK_ITER_MT);
    lua_setmetatable(L, -2);

    /* Allocate a placeholder uservalue for the reusable block userdata */
    lua_pushnil(L);
    lua_setuservalue(L, -2);    /* iterator[1] = nil */

    return 1;   /* iterator userdata */
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 *   Module registration
 * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int luaopen_blocksci(lua_State *L)
{
    /* ---- Block userdata metatable ---- */
    luaL_newmetatable(L, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_pushvalue(L, -1);                 /* duplicate metatable */
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "__index");       /* mt.__index = mt */
    luaL_setfuncs(L, block_methods, 0);
    lua_pushcfunction(L, lua_Block_gc);
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "__gc");
    lua_pop(L, 1);                        /* pop block metatable */

    /* ---- Iterator userdata metatable ---- */
    luaL_newmetatable(L, BLOCK_ITER_MT);
    lua_pushvalue(L, -1);
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "__index");
    luaL_setfuncs(L, iterator_methods, 0);
    lua_pushcfunction(L, lua_BlockIter_gc);
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "__gc");
    lua_pop(L, 1);                        /* pop iterator metatable */

    /* ---- Module table ---- */
    lua_newtable(L);
    lua_pushcfunction(L, lua_blocksci_open);
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "open");
    return 1;   /* return module table */
}
```

---

## 3.  How to compile & test

```bash
# 1) Save the file as blocksci_lua.c
# 2) Build the shared library (adjust include/lib paths for your Lua version)
gcc -shared -fPIC -std=c++17 -I/usr/include/lua5.4 \
    -o blocksci.so blocksci_lua.c -llua5.4 -lstdc++

# 3) In a Lua REPL (Lua 5.4+)
$ lua
> local bs = require "blocksci"
> local db = bs.open("/tmp/blocksci_dummy")
> db:for_each(function(b) if b:height() % 10000000 == 0 then
>        print("Reached", b:height()) end; return true end)
```

You should see a line printed roughly every ten million blocks (the mock iterator is cheap, so the loop runs instantly).  

When you replace the mock BlockSci API with the **real** one, the same Lua code will now walk the **actual 800 M‑block** dataset with only one Lua call per block and virtually no per‑iteration allocation.

---

## 4.  Extending the binding (optional suggestions)

| Feature | How to add it |
|--------|---------------|
| **Transaction‑level callbacks** | Expose a `block:transactions()` iterator that returns a lightweight `Tx` userdata; implement a similar hot‑loop in C. |
| **Parallel iteration** | Add a `db:parallel_for_each(callback, nthreads)` that spawns worker threads, each with its own iterator copy (BlockSci supports thread‑local iterators). |
| **Column‑style API** (like pandas) | Provide `db:select{height=true, time=true}` that builds a Lua table of column vectors after the iteration finishes (use the same hot loop but push values into pre‑allocated Lua arrays). |
| **Error handling** | Convert C++ exceptions to Lua errors via a wrapper macro around every public C function. |
| **Zero‑copy hash** | If the real BlockSci returns a binary 32‑byte hash, expose it as a Lua `string` (binary) and let the user decide whether to hex‑encode. |

Feel free to copy/paste the code above, replace the mock BlockSci functions with the real ones, and you’ll have a performant, user‑friendly Lua API that lets analysts write per‑block Python‑style logic while keeping the tight C++ iteration core. Happy hacking!
